	<text>
		<body>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>Feb. 16 1860</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
				<p>Dear Sir&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have the pleasure to hand<lb/> you enclosed <persName>Ottenheimer Bro&#39;s</persName> Check for<lb/> &#36;9.50&#47;100 for 3 Books sent to me through <persName>Mr<lb/> Abecasis</persName> in <date>December</date> last.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I was not a little surprised the other day<lb/> to be informed by <persName>Mr Osterberg</persName> with whom<lb/> I left in the year <date>1855</date> your remaining<lb/> 7 Bibles and 12 Copies of <persName>Dias</persName> letters<lb/> subject to your order&#44; that these books were<lb/> still in his store&#44; and have never been called<lb/> for.  I must candidly tell you my friend&#44; this<lb/> is bad management of your business affairs.<lb/>  Perceiving that your property was not properly<lb/> cared for in <persName>Mr O&#39;s</persName> store&#44; being stowed away<lb/> in some damp place&#44; &#38; after examining the books&#44;<lb/> finding one Bible &#38; several of the small books badly<lb/> damaged&#44; I concluded to take them again in<lb/> my possession to <placeName>No 130 Duane St.</placeName> where<lb/> I shall be ready to deliver them to any party&#44;<lb/> you may be pleased to designate.  I trust<lb/> you collected since all the bills for the unpaid<lb/> Bibles which I distributed in <date>1855</date> according<lb/> to your instruction.  Soliciting your further<lb/> requests&#44; I remain Your obedt servt</p>
			<p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">Lazarus Arnold</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(10)"><placeName>130 Duane</placeName></p>
		</body>
